elements.content: Isostructural CoII and MnII organic frameworks with anionic frameworks and counterions (Me2NH2)+, namely {[M2Cl2(BTC)4/3]·(Me2NH2)+ 2·4/3H2O} n (M = Co (1) and Mn (2)), have been constructed by one-pot synthesis. Complexes 1 and 2 take paddle-wheel-like dinuclear metal cluster-based three-dimensional structures. Thermogravimetric analysis and variable-temperature powder X-ray diffraction spectra suggested that 1 displays better thermal stability than 2. Both exhibit relatively high proton conductivities at 65% relative humidity (RH) and room temperature (σ > 2.5 × 10–4 S cm–1); however, complex 1 possesses the better cycling capability and stability with E a = 0.21 eV under 65% RH.

elements.content:
Two anionic metal−organic frameworks have been constructed with a one-pot method, and they exhibit high proton conductivities due to the existence of lattice water molecules and Me2NH2 + cations.

Introduction

Proton conductivities of inorganic, organic, or inorganic–organic hybrid compounds, such as metal oxide, Nafion, and metal–organic frameworks (MOFs), have been researched due to their applications in sensors and fuel cells. Generally, proton carriers H3O+/H+ provided by acid or OH groups are needed in these materials. Moreover, proton-conducting pathways comprised of a H-bond network are also required for conducting protons. Recently, MOFs as an intriguing class of crystalline and inorganic–organic hybrid material have attracted much attention not only for their conventional properties in gas storage and selective separation but for catalytic properties and electrical conductivity, in particular, proton conductivity. According to previous works, to obtain MOFs with high proton conductivities, one of the simplest and most effective methods is to introduce proton carriers such as (Me2NH2)+, H3O+, and HSO4 – as counterions directly into the pores of MOFs.

Two anionic metal-organic frameworks have been constructed with a one-pot method, and they exhibit high proton conductivities due to the existence of lattice water molecules and Me2NH2 + cations.

Introduction

Proton conductivities of inorganic, organic, or inorganic-organic hybrid compounds, such as metal oxide, Nafion, and metal-organic frameworks (MOFs), have been researched due to their applications in sensors and fuel cells. Generally, proton carriers H3O+/H+ provided by acid or OH groups are needed in these materials. Moreover, proton-conducting pathways comprised of a H-bond network are also required for conducting protons. Recently, MOFs as an intriguing class of crystalline and inorganic-organic hybrid material have attracted much attention not only for their conventional properties in gas storage and selective separation but for catalytic properties and electrical conductivity, in particular, proton conductivity. According to previous works, to obtain MOFs with high proton conductivities, one of the simplest and most effective methods is to introduce proton carriers such as (Me2NH2)+, H3O+, and HSO4 - as counterions directly into the pores of MOFs.

elements.content: Because of the synthetic challenge of anionic frameworks, MOFs with high proton conductivities have been less reported. Among various synthetic methods, the solvothermal technique is effective and easy to carry out, and in situ reaction of organic solvents and ligands usually occurs. Therefore, the introduction of (Me2NH2)+ becomes easy and fast through the solvothermal reaction. According to the literature, (Me2NH2)+ could be generated in situ by the addition of N,N′-dimethylacetamide (DMAc) or N,N′-dimethylformamide (DMF) under solvothermal conditions.

Among various synthetic methods, the solvothermal technique is effective and easy to carry out, and in situ reaction of organic solvents and ligands usually occurs. Therefore, the introduction of (Me2NH2)+ becomes easy and fast through the solvothermal reaction. According to the literature, (Me2NH2)+ could be generated in situ by the addition of N,N'-dimethylacetamide (DMAc) or N,N'-dimethylformamide (DMF) under solvothermal conditions.

elements.content: It is well-known that 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (H3BTC) has been widely used to prepare functional MOFs due to the unique structural symmetry and various coordination modes. To obtain MOFs with proton conductivity, our approach is to introduce (Me2NH2)+ as counterions into the pores of MOFs. Herein, two CoII and MnII anionic MOFs derived from H3BTC, namely {[Co2Cl2(BTC)4/3]·(Me2NH2)+ 2·4/3H2O} n (1) and {[Mn2Cl2(BTC)4/3]·(Me2NH2)+ 2·4/3H2O} n (2), have been successfully constructed and structurally characterized. Reddish-brown (1) and colorless crystals (2) were obtained by the solvothermal reaction of CoCl2·6H2O/MnCl2·4H2O, H3BTC, and DMAc/CH3CN at 160 °C. The synthetic methods are applicable to the assembly of other related functional MOFs. It is revealed that both exhibit good proton conductivities and different conductivities under distinct conditions.

elements.content: All metal salts, H3BTC, and organic solvents were of reagent grade and employed as purchased. The powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) spectra were obtained under a Rigaku D/Max-2500 diffractometer with a Cu target tube and a graphite monochromator. Variable-temperature PXRD was recorded on a PANalytical X’pert PRO diffractometer at 40 kV and 30 mA with a Cu target tube and a graphite monochromator. The simulated PXRD spectra were from the single-crystal data and the Mercury (Hg) program obtained free from the Web site at http://www.iucr.org. IR spectra were obtained in 4000–400 cm–1 on a Bruker Tensor 27 OPUS FT-IR spectrometer employing KBr pellets. Thermogravimetric analyses (TGAs) were carried out on a Rigaku standard TG-DTA analyzer under N2 atmosphere with a heating rate of 10 °C min–1 and employing an empty Al2O3 crucible as reference. Alternating current (AC) impedance measurements with sample pellets (6 mm in diameter) were performed by the conventional quasi-four-probe method on the Zennium electrochemical workstation employing silver paste and silver wires. The frequency range of the AC source is 1–4 × 106 Hz. The amplitude of AC voltage is 100 mV. The humidity is controlled by different saturated aqueous salt solutions.
elements.clean_text:
Experimental Section

Materials and Physical Measurements

All metal salts, H3BTC, and organic solvents were of reagent grade and employed as purchased. The powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) spectra were obtained under a Rigaku D/Max-2500 diffractometer with a Cu target tube and a graphite monochromator. Variable-temperature PXRD was recorded on a PANalytical X'pert PRO diffractometer at 40 kV and 30 mA with a Cu target tube and a graphite monochromator. The simulated PXRD spectra were from the single-crystal data and the Mercury (Hg) program obtained free from the Web site at http://www.iucr.org. IR spectra were obtained in 4000-400 cm-1 on a Bruker Tensor 27 OPUS FT-IR spectrometer employing KBr pellets. Thermogravimetric analyses (TGAs) were carried out on a Rigaku standard TG-DTA analyzer under N2 atmosphere with a heating rate of 10 °C min-1 and employing an empty Al2O3 crucible as reference. Alternating current (AC) impedance measurements with sample pellets (6 mm in diameter) were performed by the conventional quasi-four-probe method on the Zennium electrochemical workstation employing silver paste and silver wires. The frequency range of the AC source is 1-4 × 106 Hz. The amplitude of AC voltage is 100 mV. The humidity is controlled by different saturated aqueous salt solutions.

elements.content: CoCl2·6H2O (1 mmol, 238 mg) and H3btc (0.5 mmol, 105 mg) were dissolved in 10 mL of mixed solvent (V DMAc:V MeCN = 6:4). The reaction mixture was then heated at 160 °C for 72 h sealed in a Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. Upon cooling to room temperature (RT) over 12 h, reddish-brown crystal blocks were obtained with a yield of ∼50% based on CoII.

elements.content: The X-ray single-crystal diffraction data of 1 and 2 were measured with a Rigaku SCX-mini diffractometer at 293(2) K with Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) by the mode of ω scan. Program CrystalClear was utilized for integration of the diffraction profiles. Direct method was used to solve the structure through the SHELXS program of the SHELXTL package, and the structure was refined by full-matrix least-squares methods with SHELXL. The non-H atoms were identified by successive difference Fourier syntheses and refined with anisotropic thermal parameters on F 2. The H atoms of H3BTC were added theoretically on the specific atoms. Because of the limitation on the crystal quality, the H atoms in H2O and (Me2NH2)+ were not assigned. A summary of the crystal data and structure refinements for 1 and 2 is given in . The selected bond lengths and angles are provided in Tables S1 and S2. For better crystal data to be obtained, complexes 1 and 2 were also measured on a Bruker D8 QUEST diffractometer at 100(2) K with Mo Kα radiation by ω scan mode. The solvent molecules and disordered organic cations in 1 and 2 were removed by the SQUEEZE program in PLATON.
elements.clean_text:
X-ray Data Collection and Structure Determinations

The X-ray single-crystal diffraction data of 1 and 2 were measured with a Rigaku SCX-mini diffractometer at 293(2) K with Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) by the mode of ω scan. Program CrystalClear was utilized for integration of the diffraction profiles. Direct method was used to solve the structure through the SHELXS program of the SHELXTL package, and the structure was refined by full-matrix least-squares methods with SHELXL. The non-H atoms were identified by successive difference Fourier syntheses and refined with anisotropic thermal parameters on F 2. The H atoms of H3BTC were added theoretically on the specific atoms. Because of the limitation on the crystal quality, the H atoms in H2O and (Me2NH2)+ were not assigned. A summary of the crystal data and structure refinements for 1 and 2 is given in . The selected bond lengths and angles are provided in Tables S1 and S2. For better crystal data to be obtained, complexes 1 and 2 were also measured on a Bruker D8 QUEST diffractometer at 100(2) K with Mo Kα radiation by ω scan mode. The solvent molecules and disordered organic cations in 1 and 2 were removed by the SQUEEZE program in PLATON.

Complexes 1 and 2 are isostructural with a similar structure as Cu3(BTC)2 (HKUST-1) and include a paddle-wheel-like Co2 or Mn2 cluster as secondary building unit (SBU); thus, herein, only the structure of 1 is represented shortly. In 1, unlike HKUST-1, the chloride ions replace oxygen atoms to make the framework negative, and (Me2NH2)+ as counterions exist in the pores. It crystallizes in the high-symmetry space group Fm3̅m of the cubic system. The calculated result by employing SHAPE 2.0 indicates that the geometry of the five-coordinative CoII or MnII could be viewed as spherical square pyramid (SSP) (), accomplished by four O atoms from BTC3– ligands and one Cl atom. Two adjacent CoII ions are linked by four carboxylate groups (a). The structure of 1 comprises an infinite number of dinuclear cobalt paddlewheel SBUs interconnected by the tricarboxylate ligand, leading to a 3D framework bearing 3D channels (b). Moreover, the guest water molecules and disorderly protonated dimethylamine cations exist in the pores (c). The porosity of 1 calculated by PLATON is 46.9% of the unit cell (with water molecules removed). However, N2 adsorption isotherms of activated 1 and 2 measured at 77 K suggest that both of them have almost no adsorption capability, and the frameworks are not stable after vacuum degassing (Figure S1). From a topological point of view, 1 is a typical (3,4)-connected 3D tbo framework with a point symbol of (62.82.102)3(63)4 if each Co2 cluster serves as a 4-connected node and each BTC group regards as 3-connected node, respectively (d).

Results and Discussion

Description of Crystal Structure

Complexes 1 and 2 are isostructural with a similar structure as Cu3(BTC)2 (HKUST-1) and include a paddle-wheel-like Co2 or Mn2 cluster as secondary building unit (SBU); thus, herein, only the structure of 1 is represented shortly. In 1, unlike HKUST-1, the chloride ions replace oxygen atoms to make the framework negative, and (Me2NH2)+ as counterions exist in the pores. It crystallizes in the high-symmetry space group Fm3̅m of the cubic system. The calculated result by employing SHAPE 2.0 indicates that the geometry of the five-coordinative CoII or MnII could be viewed as spherical square pyramid (SSP) (), accomplished by four O atoms from BTC3- ligands and one Cl atom. Two adjacent CoII ions are linked by four carboxylate groups (a). The structure of 1 comprises an infinite number of dinuclear cobalt paddlewheel SBUs interconnected by the tricarboxylate ligand, leading to a 3D framework bearing 3D channels (b). Moreover, the guest water molecules and disorderly protonated dimethylamine cations exist in the pores (c). The porosity of 1 calculated by PLATON is 46.9% of the unit cell (with water molecules removed). However, N2 adsorption isotherms of activated 1 and 2 measured at 77 K suggest that both of them have almost no adsorption capability, and the frameworks are not stable after vacuum degassing (Figure S1). From a topological point of view, 1 is a typical (3,4)-connected 3D tbo framework with a point symbol of (62.82.102)3(63)4 if each Co2 cluster serves as a 4-connected node and each BTC group regards as 3-connected node, respectively (d).

For the thermal stabilities of 1 and 2 to be corroborated, TGAs were carried out. The results suggest that almost all of the guest molecules were removed below ∼350 °C, and no further weight loss was observed until 440 and 520 °C, respectively (Figure S2). The PXRD patterns of 1 and 2 with crushed crystalline state were performed to confirm their phase purities before proton conductive measurements. As shown in , the PXRD patterns at ambient temperature of 1 and 2 are consistent with the simulated ones from the single-crystal diffraction data, revealing the phase purity of the samples. Notably, the peak differences in intensity between the simulated and experimental patterns may result from the preferred orientation of the lattice face. Moreover, the simulated PXRD pattern of 1 agrees with the measured one after being soaked in familiar solvents (such as MeOH, EtOH, and CH2Cl2) for 24 h, implying the good solvent stability of 1 (Figure S3a). Variable-temperature PXRD shows that the samples retain their crystallinity up to approximately 250 and 200 °C for 1 and 2, respectively (Figure S3b and c, SI).

Generally, the proton-conducting property of MOFs is influenced by two main factors: relative humidity (RH) and temperature. elements.clean_text:
Proton Conduction

The free protonated organic amine cations as proton carriers and water chains as proton-conducting pathways make 1 and 2 suitable for potential proton-conducting solid materials. Generally, the proton-conducting property of MOFs is influenced by two main factors: relative humidity (RH) and temperature. Thus, the proton conductivities of the solid samples are investigated by AC impedance spectroscopy. Most of the studies on proton conductivity were carried out under the conditions of 98% or 95% RH, whereas the samples at relatively lower RH have been investigated less.

elements.content: For 1, we aimed to obtain conductivity in the form of Nyquist plots (Z′ versus Z″) at different temperatures under relatively low humidity conditions (65% RH), employing a compacted pellet of the powder sample, as shown in . They display one semicircle with a characteristic spur at low frequencies, indicating the blocking of H+ ions at the silver electrodes. The conductivities of the samples were derived from the impedance values by employing the equation σ = d Z · S where σ is the conductivity (S cm–1), d is the thickness (cm) of the measured sample, S stands for the electrode area (cm2), and Z represents the impedance (Ω). For 1, d and S are 0.201 cm and 0.2826 cm2, respectively, and thus the σ values are 5.93 × 10–4, 6.77 × 10–4, 7.26 × 10–4, 8.08 × 10–4, 9.48 × 10–4, 1.03 × 10–3, and 1.19 × 10–3 S cm–1 at 19, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, and 50 °C, respectively, which are comparable to the reported MOFs (a and ). The activation energy (E a) for the proton transfer derived from the bulk conductivity of 1 was estimated from the impedance spectra recorded at 65% RH between 19 and 50 °C to be 0.21 eV (b). The proton conductivities of 1 at 53 and 33% RH (19 °C) have also been measured (Figure S4a and b), and the σ values are 9.21 × 10–8 and 4.45 × 10–6 S cm–1, respectively, indicating that the higher RH is conducive to an increase in proton conductivity if the MOFs are stable enough. In addition, the PXRD pattern of the tested sample matches well with the simulated one, suggesting that the tested sample stays the same and exhibits good cycling ability (a).
elements.clean_text: For 1, we aimed to obtain conductivity in the form of Nyquist plots (Z' versus Z") at different temperatures under relatively low humidity conditions (65% RH), employing a compacted pellet of the powder sample, as shown in . They display one semicircle with a characteristic spur at low frequencies, indicating the blocking of H+ ions at the silver electrodes. The conductivities of the samples were derived from the impedance values by employing the equation     σ =   d   Z ⋅ S     where σ is the conductivity (S cm-1), d is the thickness (cm) of the measured sample, S stands for the electrode area (cm2), and Z represents the impedance (Ω). For 1, d and S are 0.201 cm and 0.2826 cm2, respectively, and thus the σ values are 5.93 × 10-4, 6.77 × 10-4, 7.26 × 10-4, 8.08 × 10-4, 9.48 × 10-4, 1.03 × 10-3, and 1.19 × 10-3 S cm-1 at 19, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, and 50 °C, respectively, which are comparable to the reported MOFs (a and ). The activation energy (E a) for the proton transfer derived from the bulk conductivity of 1 was estimated from the impedance spectra recorded at 65% RH between 19 and 50 °C to be 0.21 eV (b). The proton conductivities of 1 at 53 and 33% RH (19 °C) have also been measured (Figure S4a and b), and the σ values are 9.21 × 10-8 and 4.45 × 10-6 S cm-1, respectively, indicating that the higher RH is conducive to an increase in proton conductivity if the MOFs are stable enough. In addition, the PXRD pattern of the tested sample matches well with the simulated one, suggesting that the tested sample stays the same and exhibits good cycling ability (a).

Complex 1 shows better proton conduction and cycling capability. The increase of the conductance is due to the adsorption of the water molecules and the improved conductivity may originate from proton transfer, where water molecules serve as proton donors.

elements.content: By employing 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylate as 3-node ligand, two functional 3D MOFs have been successfully obtained with solvothermal reactions. They have a similar structure with HKUST-1 containing paddle-wheel-like dimeric CoII or MnII clusters and exhibit high proton conductivities with dimethylamine cations as proton carriers and lattice water chain as proton-conducting pathways, especially for 1. The synthetic methods may provide a new way to synthesize other functional MOFs. Further studies of cluster-based MOFs with better proton conductivities are under way in our group.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

By employing 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylate as 3-node ligand, two functional 3D MOFs have been successfully obtained with solvothermal reactions. They have a similar structure with HKUST-1 containing paddle-wheel-like dimeric CoII or MnII clusters and exhibit high proton conductivities with dimethylamine cations as proton carriers and lattice water chain as proton-conducting pathways, especially for 1. The synthetic methods may provide a new way to synthesize other functional MOFs. Further studies of cluster-based MOFs with better proton conductivities are under way in our group.

cln_elements.content: For the thermal stabilities of 1 and 2 to be corroborated, TGAs were carried out. The results suggest that almost all of the guest molecules were removed below ∼350 °C, and no further weight loss was observed until 440 and 520 °C, respectively (Figure S2). The PXRD patterns of 1 and 2 with crushed crystalline state were performed to confirm their phase purities before proton conductive measurements. As shown in , the PXRD patterns at ambient temperature of 1 and 2 are consistent with the simulated ones from the single-crystal diffraction data, revealing the phase purity of the samples. Notably, the peak differences in intensity between the simulated and experimental patterns may result from the preferred orientation of the lattice face. Moreover, the simulated PXRD pattern of 1 agrees with the measured one after being soaked in familiar solvents (such as MeOH, EtOH, and CH2Cl2) for 24 h, implying the good solvent stability of 1 (Figure S3a). Variable-temperature PXRD shows that the samples retain their crystallinity up to approximately 250 and 200 °C for 1 and 2, respectively (Figure S3b and c, SI).
cln_elements.clean_text:
TGAs and PXRD Patterns

For the thermal stabilities of 1 and 2 to be corroborated, TGAs were carried out. The results suggest that almost all of the guest molecules were removed below ~350 °C, and no further weight loss was observed until 440 and 520 °C, respectively (Figure S2). The PXRD patterns of 1 and 2 with crushed crystalline state were performed to confirm their phase purities before proton conductive measurements. As shown in , the PXRD patterns at ambient temperature of 1 and 2 are consistent with the simulated ones from the single-crystal diffraction data, revealing the phase purity of the samples. Notably, the peak differences in intensity between the simulated and experimental patterns may result from the preferred orientation of the lattice face. Moreover, the simulated PXRD pattern of 1 agrees with the measured one after being soaked in familiar solvents (such as MeOH, EtOH, and CH2Cl2) for 24 h, implying the good solvent stability of 1 (Figure S3a). Variable-temperature PXRD shows that the samples retain their crystallinity up to approximately 250 and 200 °C for 1 and 2, respectively (Figure S3b and c, SI).
